This award sought to assess the present and future flood mitigation services of wetland infrastructure across two cities; Gresham, OR, USA, and Valdivia, Chile, and to draw lessons from these sites to reduce flood risk in cities across the globe. The wetlands of these cities differed in two key ways that warranted study: in Gresham, OR, wetlands were all constructed, and made up less than 8% of the citys area; in Valdivia, Chile, wetlands were all natural and made up greater than 20% of the citys area. The wetlands of these cities were similar in terms of their geospatial setting and present climate, and that they were being used explicitly to reduce flood risk. These sites afforded a unique opportunity to compare two different but potentially complementary approaches to wetland management to reduce flood risk under similar climate conditions. This work had many outcomes, including but not limited to:


1) Helped to understand the limits of flood mitigation from urban wetlands as they are currently configured and under current climate conditions;


2) Provided instructional findings showing how practitioners may alter wetland characteristics like area, location, and drainage rates and timing to reduce flood risk under future climate and land cover conditions;


3) Generated three publications in peer-reviewed scientific journals, with two more in review and two more in preparation;


4) Promoted carbon sequestration in wetlands via a municipal workshop in Valdivia urban development with zero net carbon emissions;


5) Provided data used in a grant proposal, under review, for riverine wetland conservation in Santiago de Chile;


6) Provided data used in the creation of a constructed wetland in Valdivia, Chile to reduce community flooding;


6) Provided findings used in community workshops on conservation efforts in the Johnson Creek Watershed in Gresham, OR;


7) Generated shapefiles and hydrological models to be used by city practitioners in the US and Chile;


8) Created opportunities for students and researchers on both continents to learn field techniques for measuring wetland hydrology, statistical techniques for characterizing wetland hydrology and rainfall characteristics, and geospatial techniques for assessing the effects of changes of landcover on watershed hydrology;


9) Provided data and and time to mentor two altREU students from underrepresented communities develop wetland water quality research projects;


10) Provided with me the financial support and time necessary to apply for work after project completion, resulting in me getting hired as a researcher for a state energy department.


Lessons drawn from this work will build upon the existing literature on the use of wetlands and other nature-based solutions to reducing flood risk. Hopefully, this work will serve to reduce flood risk in other cities around the world as it is currently helping to reduce flood risk in Gresham and Valdivia.					Last Modified: 11/21/2024

